ifferent from that in which corrupt practices are uncommon. A central feature of this difference is the role of beliefs about the prevalence of corruption and the reliability of government as an enforcer of rules ostensibly constraining official venality. Anticorruption reform in a setting of widespread corruption is a problem not only of reducing corrupt payoffs, but also of changing broadly shared expectations of venality. The book explores differences in institutional design choices about anticorruption agencies, appropriate incentive structures, and underlying constitutional designs that contribute to the disparate outcomes in Hong Kong and mainland China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCorruption (Politique)xChinexHongkong. 0aCorruption (Politique)xChine. 0aCorruption (Politique)xPréventionxChinexHongkong. 0aCorruption (Politique)xPréventionxChine. 0aCorruption (Politique)xÉtudes de casxChinaxHongkongxChinaxChinaxHong Kong. 0aCorruption (Politique)xÉtudes de casxPrévention. 0aPolitical corruptionvCase studies. 0aPolitical corruptionxCase studiesxPrevention. 0aPolitical corruptionxCase studies. 0aPolitical corruptionxChinaxHong Kong. 0aPolitical corruptionxChina. 0aPolitical corruptionxPreventionvCase studies. 0aPolitical corruptionxPreventionxChinaxHong Kong. 0aPolitical corruptionxPreventionxChina. 0aPolitical corruptionzChinaxPrevention. 0aPolitical corruptionzChinazHong KongxPrevention. 0aPolitical corruptionzChinazHong Kong. 0aPolitical corruptionzChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Affairs & Administration.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674040519zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674040519423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674040519/original  aEBA_BAC